---
import ComingSoonRoomLayout from '../layouts/ComingSoonRoomLayout.astro';
---
<ComingSoonRoomLayout
  room="chronicle"
  title="Chronicle Room"
  subtitle="Two hundred and forty years on a single timeline."
  sourceId="coming-soon-chronicle"
>
  <p>
    The Chronicle Room walks the visitor down a wall-length timeline of
    America's school trust — from the Confederation Congress committee that
    reserved Section 16 in May 1785, through the Northwest Ordinance two
    years later, the long century of admission acts that carried the
    architecture westward, the doubled-section grants of the 1850s, the
    quadrupled-section grants of the 1890s, the final admissions of Alaska
    and Hawaii in 1959, and on into the modern reckoning that the present
    generation has begun. Each anchor on the timeline points the reader
    into other rooms — into a state dossier, a court opinion, a primary
    source, a chapter of <em>Schools of the Republic</em>.
  </p>
  <p>
    <strong>Why this room matters.</strong> The school trust is a
    multi-generational story. It can only be understood as a span of time
    longer than any single life. The Chronicle Room is the room where a
    reader can finally see the shape of the whole — the moments when the
    experiment expanded, the moments when it lost ground, and the moments
    when it held.
  </p>
  <p>
    <strong>The shadow timeline.</strong> A second, fainter line will run
    parallel above the first — the counterfactual: what the trust would be
    worth today if it had been managed as the framers designed. Somewhere
    between eighty and one hundred and twenty billion dollars of forgone
    value, depending on how the loss is computed.
  </p>
  <p>
    <strong>Being planned.</strong> The 1785 entry first. The
    doubled-section threshold of 1850 second.
  </p>
</ComingSoonRoomLayout>
